WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.200
Thank you very much, Hadley, and thank all of you for coming to the conference.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:20.559
I hope you had a great first few days and great night last night.

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:27.680
It's a great privilege for us at rstudio to be here with all of you this week.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:33.000
Today I'm going to talk about machine learning with TensorFlow and R.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.320
For those of you who don't know, TensorFlow is an open source project from Google.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:40.400
It actually came out just a little bit over two years ago.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:45.720
And from the day it came out, I have been excited about what we could do with TensorFlow

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:50.360
from R. And for the last about 18 months, me and some

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:56.320
others at rstudio have been working on R interfaces to TensorFlow, and I'm really excited today

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.560
to share a lot of that work with all of you.

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:04.360
So I'm going to start by giving an introduction to kind of what is TensorFlow, what are the

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:08.800
core constituent parts of TensorFlow, and how does it work at kind of a low level.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:14.000
The principal application, but by no means the exclusive application of TensorFlow is

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:15.360
for deep learning.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:18.680
So I want to talk a little bit conceptually what is deep learning, how does it work, what

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:21.559
is it useful for, not useful for.

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:25.279
And then I want to get into the work we've done in R to provide interfaces to TensorFlow

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:31.080
for doing both deep learning and for other types of machine learning.

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:33.800
So let's start with what is TensorFlow.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:39.360
And you might offhand just say, oh, TensorFlow, that's a deep learning library.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:43.639
It is that, but it's actually considerably more than that.

00:01:43.639 --> 00:01:48.120
TensorFlow is actually a very general purpose numerical computing library.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:54.919
And in R, we have a long history of providing interfaces to numerical computing libraries.

00:01:54.919 --> 00:02:00.400
The original S language was the motivator for it was to provide interfaces to Fortran

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:02.279
numerical computing libraries.

00:02:02.279 --> 00:02:08.639
And today in R, we wrap that code, we wrap code from Blasses, we wrap code from the Eigen

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.160
C++ library, the Armadillo C++ library.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:15.960
In R, we love numerical computing libraries, and we love creating lovely interfaces to

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.199
them from R.

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:20.679
So this is a new numerical computing library, and it has some interesting attributes.

00:02:20.679 --> 00:02:23.639
First of all, it's open source, as I said before.

00:02:23.639 --> 00:02:25.880
Second of all, it's actually hardware independent.

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:32.520
So a TensorFlow program can run equally well on a CPU and take advantage of all the cores

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:37.240
on a CPU, and that's actually using the Eigen and Blass libraries that we already use from

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:38.240
R.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.399
But it can also run on a GPU or multiple GPUs.

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:46.679
And there's even a thing that Google has created called a TPU, a tensor processing unit, which

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:50.800
is hardware that is designed to run TensorFlow programs.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.000
And there will actually be other instances of this in the future.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:56.399
So hardware independence is a really cool attribute of TensorFlow.

00:02:56.399 --> 00:03:01.360
Another really cool attribute of it for numerical computing is that it supports automatic differentiation.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:06.839
And that's used extensively in the deep learning parts of TensorFlow.

00:03:06.839 --> 00:03:12.000
The other thing is it was built from the ground up for deployment, and scalable deployment,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.440
so it supports distributed execution, it supports very, very large datasets.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.919
So it's a really cool numerical computing library that we can do a lot of things with

00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:21.240
in R.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:24.360
And that's kind of the first bullet point of why our users should care.

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:27.559
New numerical computing library, what can we do with it?

00:03:27.559 --> 00:03:33.279
One of the other cool things about it is that there are many built-in optimization algorithms

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:35.919
that don't require that all the data is in RAM.

00:03:35.919 --> 00:03:39.919
So typically, the optimization algorithms we use require that we manage to get the whole

00:03:39.919 --> 00:03:40.919
dataset in RAM.

00:03:40.919 --> 00:03:45.039
But now we can have a 10 gigabyte dataset, and we actually feed data to models just a

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:48.279
small batch at a time, and the optimizer will work correctly.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:53.080
So it lets us do modeling and machine learning on very large datasets without having to have

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.199
a huge amount of RAM.

00:03:55.199 --> 00:03:58.880
Another piece of TensorFlow that's interesting is that typically when we think about building

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:02.639
a model in R and then we want to deploy it, we actually need to bring R code along with

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:04.199
it in the deployment.

00:04:04.199 --> 00:04:08.520
But the whole design of TensorFlow is that when you build a TensorFlow model, you can

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:10.279
deploy it entirely separate.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:12.600
You don't need R or Python or any other code.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:13.600
It's just a C++ runtime.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:15.679
So this is actually really cool, too.

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:22.200
So the last piece, I think we're really good in R at writing interfaces to all kinds of

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:26.119
things in computing, and I think we can do a lot of wonderful things with R interfaces

00:04:26.119 --> 00:04:27.760
to TensorFlow.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:32.359
So some of the basics of TensorFlow, where does that name TensorFlow, what are tensors,

00:04:32.359 --> 00:04:36.559
what's flowing, just to give you a baseline of what we're talking about here before we

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:38.559
get into talking about deep learning.

00:04:38.559 --> 00:04:43.160
So tensors, actually everyone here already works with tensors pretty much all the time.

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:45.260
Tensors are just multidimensional arrays.

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:50.619
So in R, the core data type vector and matrices, those are our tensors.

00:04:50.619 --> 00:04:57.140
So a one-dimensional tensor is just an R vector, a two-dimensional tensor is an R matrix, and

00:04:57.140 --> 00:05:01.380
then you get into 3D and 4D arrays, which R also supports.

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:05.459
A 0D tensor is a scalar, which R does not have a scalar data type, but you can think

00:05:05.459 --> 00:05:08.739
of it conceptually as a vector that's always of length one.

00:05:08.739 --> 00:05:13.579
So you're going to be dealing with tensors, and the good news is we already deal with

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:14.579
tensors all the time.

00:05:14.899 --> 00:05:16.820
So there's really nothing new to learn there.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:21.140
I want to give some examples of tensor data, kind of how it plays out in TensorFlow.

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:26.059
And one of the things to remember, if you think about a data frame, each row is an observation.

00:05:26.059 --> 00:05:32.779
So there's always a dimension that's dedicated to observations or samples.

00:05:32.779 --> 00:05:37.140
So in the case of a 2D tensor, I can just take a data frame, turn it into a matrix,

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:39.339
and now I've got a 2D tensor.

00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:42.500
That's something we're all familiar with in R.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:47.220
Time series data, or sequence data, is an example of a 3D tensor, even though sometimes

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:48.820
that's represented in 2D.

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:53.660
You can think of a time series object in R. If you think about a time series, you're actually

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:58.739
considering not just the observations, but what happens to the observations over time.

00:05:58.739 --> 00:06:01.940
So it's really a 3D entity that you're analyzing.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:07.660
It's the features, the time steps, and then groupings of those.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:09.899
Image data is an example of a 4D tensor.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:13.019
Again, you might think of an image as a 3D tensor.

00:06:13.019 --> 00:06:18.940
You'd say, well, it has height, and width, and depth, which is color channels, like red,

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:19.859
green, and blue.

00:06:19.859 --> 00:06:20.579
That's 3D.

00:06:20.579 --> 00:06:23.820
But then if you consider samples, again, you end up with a 4D tensor.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:27.779
And similarly, a video would be like a 5D tensor, because it's multiple frames,

00:06:27.779 --> 00:06:28.700
multiple images.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:31.380
So that's kind of how tensors end up getting represented.

00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:34.980
So what is this flow business that we're talking about?

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:39.339
TensorFlow programs are not just like an R script that executes.

00:06:39.339 --> 00:06:42.579
You actually build up a data flow graph.

00:06:42.579 --> 00:06:46.420
And what happens is those tensors, the data, flow through the graph.

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:50.299
And the operations in the graph, and basically their operations in the graph.

00:06:50.299 --> 00:06:53.619
So an example of an operation inside a TensorFlow graph is like a matrix

00:06:53.619 --> 00:06:58.619
multiplication, or the addition of a bias term, or taking gradients, or applying

00:06:58.619 --> 00:07:00.459
some kind of optimizer.

00:07:00.459 --> 00:07:04.339
So those are like functions that operate on the data, and it's all put together

00:07:04.339 --> 00:07:05.140
inside a graph.

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:10.019
And I'll kind of explain why that's beneficial in a moment.

00:07:10.019 --> 00:07:13.179
When you work with TensorFlow, you don't actually program.

00:07:13.179 --> 00:07:15.260
You can program the graph explicitly.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:16.859
There's interfaces to do that.

00:07:16.859 --> 00:07:19.100
But typically, you actually write much, much higher level code.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:22.579
And I'm going to explain this R code in detail shortly.

00:07:22.579 --> 00:07:26.700
But this is an example of a model that I've written in R.

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:31.140
And that's, on the right, what it actually looks like as a TensorFlow graph.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:34.820
So the graph, when you're using high level APIs to TensorFlow,

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:35.899
is basically generated.

00:07:35.899 --> 00:07:38.480
And you don't have to reason about it at the level of the graph.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:39.700
But the graph is still there.

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:42.100
And why is this graph beneficial?

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:45.059
Well, we can actually think of other examples

00:07:45.059 --> 00:07:49.980
that we have in R of these sort of intermediate representations.

00:07:49.980 --> 00:07:52.140
So you can think of like a Shiny application.

00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:54.500
When you build inputs, and outputs, and reactives,

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:56.779
you're actually creating a graph.

00:07:56.779 --> 00:07:59.260
And then Shiny executes your graph in a way

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:01.019
that's kind of optimal and efficient.

00:08:01.019 --> 00:08:03.619
So the fact that Shiny knows the structure of your program

00:08:03.619 --> 00:08:06.899
allows it to run your program in a way that's

00:08:06.899 --> 00:08:09.059
really optimal and straightforward.

00:08:09.059 --> 00:08:13.019
When you write a dplyr code that works against a database,

00:08:13.019 --> 00:08:14.420
it generates SQL.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.260
SQL is sort of this intermediate language

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:20.179
that's then fed to a SQL query optimizer that then executes

00:08:20.179 --> 00:08:21.700
the query in an efficient way.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:24.260
So similarly, what Google wanted to do with TensorFlow

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:27.899
was, if we can get the representation of your model or your program

00:08:27.899 --> 00:08:30.899
into a graph, then we can run it really fast.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:32.580
We can run it in parallel.

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:34.140
We can run it distributed.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:35.900
We can look at the operations in your graph

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:38.780
and fuse them together when possible.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:43.580
And then the other thing is we can run this without R or Python,

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:44.659
just with C++.

00:08:44.659 --> 00:08:47.539
So really, the benefits of the graph are all

00:08:47.539 --> 00:08:51.700
about this idea of portability, performance, and scalability.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:54.099
So this does create some indirection,

00:08:54.099 --> 00:08:57.299
but I think it has a lot of benefits.

00:08:57.299 --> 00:08:59.500
So what are people using TensorFlow for?

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:01.700
I'm actually going to talk about all of these in turn.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:04.739
They're all listed on our TensorFlow for R website.

00:09:04.739 --> 00:09:06.700
A lot of people are using it for deep learning,

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:10.979
but people are also using it for a lot of classical machine learning.

00:09:10.979 --> 00:09:12.659
These are some of the examples written up,

00:09:12.659 --> 00:09:15.859
and these are all long-form blog posts that get into things people are doing.

00:09:15.859 --> 00:09:18.900
But you can see some text classification stuff,

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:22.900
some examples of trying to do predictions on really noisy data.

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:27.299
There's computer vision applications, time series applications.

00:09:27.299 --> 00:09:31.419
And I think there's these examples by actually hopeful and confident

00:09:31.419 --> 00:09:34.619
the R community, when given access to this library,

00:09:34.619 --> 00:09:38.179
is going to do some really additional interesting things that surprise us.

00:09:38.179 --> 00:09:42.099
I have one example of a project called Greta,

00:09:42.099 --> 00:09:45.500
which is similar in aims to Bugs or Stan.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:48.700
The idea is to write statistical models and fit them with MCMC.

00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:53.739
And so the way Greta works is I write a statistical model in R,

00:09:53.739 --> 00:09:57.340
not in some kind of separate specialized language.

00:09:57.340 --> 00:10:02.340
And then that model is compiled to TensorFlow, a TensorFlow graph.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:04.580
And that actually uses the R TensorFlow package.

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:08.780
And the benefit of this is, A, I'm writing in R instead of a specialized language.

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:11.659
But B, because it's using TensorFlow, I can train it on really large data sets.

00:10:11.659 --> 00:10:13.380
I can train it with GPUs.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:14.940
I can actually deploy the model.

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:17.140
So this is an example of something that really has nothing

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:19.580
to do with deep learning that people have already

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:21.460
done with the R for TensorFlow interface.

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:24.940
And I'm hopeful that there'll be more examples of this sort of thing.

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:28.380
OK, so now let's get into a little bit of what,

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:31.500
because deep learning is probably the main thing people do with TensorFlow.

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:34.059
And so I think it's important to understand kind of what is it?

00:10:34.059 --> 00:10:34.979
What is it useful for?

00:10:34.979 --> 00:10:36.059
What is it not useful for?

00:10:36.059 --> 00:10:39.659
Should we in the R community, how much should we care about it?

00:10:39.659 --> 00:10:41.260
And kind of how does it work?

00:10:41.260 --> 00:10:43.059
So I want to cover some of that ground.

00:10:43.059 --> 00:10:46.859
And then I'll talk about the R interfaces to TensorFlow.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:52.299
So at a really, really high level, deep learning

00:10:52.299 --> 00:10:55.940
is taking some input, transforming it into some output

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.299
via successive layers of representation.

00:10:58.299 --> 00:11:01.380
And when I say this really abstract to say input and output, what I mean there

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:04.859
is like observations or x data and predictions.

00:11:04.859 --> 00:11:08.619
So it's x to y, but how do we do that?

00:11:08.619 --> 00:11:11.380
We do that by taking original input, in this case,

00:11:11.380 --> 00:11:15.020
a grayscale image of a handwritten number 4.

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:17.979
That's our input, and our output is a prediction about what the digit is,

00:11:17.979 --> 00:11:19.099
the number 4.

00:11:19.099 --> 00:11:23.700
We have to successfully transform that input until we get close to the output.

00:11:23.700 --> 00:11:27.460
That's the basic mechanic of how deep learning models work.

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:28.780
So I'm talking about layers.

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:29.979
I showed four layers there.

00:11:29.979 --> 00:11:32.099
What exactly is a layer?

00:11:32.099 --> 00:11:34.859
And I'm not going to talk about the mechanics of, maybe some of you

00:11:34.859 --> 00:11:37.900
have seen this before, of neurons and how they talk to other neurons

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:38.979
and all that stuff.

00:11:38.979 --> 00:11:41.219
You can really just think of a layer, and all you really

00:11:41.219 --> 00:11:43.260
need to consider a layer as, it's a function.

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:44.900
It's a data transformation function.

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:47.380
It does a geometric transformation of data,

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:50.260
and it's parameterized by a set of weights and a bias,

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:52.020
just like a linear equation.

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:55.659
So you can think of each one of these as just a successive transformation

00:11:55.659 --> 00:11:56.419
of data.

00:11:56.419 --> 00:11:59.340
So that's all a deep learning model is, is taking some data

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:03.020
and then chaining together a bunch of transformations of the data

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:07.179
until we actually get an output, or in this case, a prediction.

00:12:07.179 --> 00:12:09.900
So when I say representations, what am I talking about?

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:12.859
We really want to take our data and transform it

00:12:12.859 --> 00:12:18.260
in a way that's closer to the domain of prediction that we're looking for.

00:12:18.260 --> 00:12:19.700
So this is a really simple example.

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:20.700
I've got raw data.

00:12:20.700 --> 00:12:24.099
I've got a bunch of points, and I want to determine

00:12:24.099 --> 00:12:27.900
whether a point, be able to predict whether a point is black or white.

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:30.500
If I change the coordinate system, all of a sudden,

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:33.179
the problem becomes really simple, because everything

00:12:33.179 --> 00:12:35.500
with x greater than zero is a black point,

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:39.299
and everything with x less than zero is a white point.

00:12:39.299 --> 00:12:41.979
So the idea is we want to transform our data

00:12:41.979 --> 00:12:45.380
so it's easier and easier to get close to the actual output

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:47.419
that we're looking for, the prediction that we're looking for.

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:50.539
If you work with conventional machine learning models,

00:12:50.539 --> 00:12:53.380
you'll know this as sort of feature engineering, where

00:12:53.380 --> 00:12:55.460
we're trying to transform our data into a form that

00:12:55.460 --> 00:12:58.380
works better for the prediction task.

00:12:58.380 --> 00:13:00.260
And in deep learning, the feature engineering

00:13:00.260 --> 00:13:02.539
is actually done in the layers.

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:07.700
The feature engineering is actually learned rather than hand coded.

00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:10.460
So back to this example of the handwritten digits,

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:13.219
and I'll explain a little bit later how this works.

00:13:13.219 --> 00:13:17.099
But basically, we're taking raw data, and these layers

00:13:17.099 --> 00:13:19.460
are trying to filter out irrelevant information,

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:22.500
like how the image actually looks.

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:25.219
And it's trying to find other things, like where are edges, what

00:13:25.219 --> 00:13:27.739
are the angle of the edges, and get closer and closer

00:13:27.739 --> 00:13:30.020
to the domain of output or prediction.

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:35.619
So you can think of it as sort of an information distillation pipeline.

00:13:35.619 --> 00:13:39.419
And so this gives us an intuition about where the word deep comes from.

00:13:39.419 --> 00:13:40.820
Why do we call this deep learning?

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:45.059
It's not because it gives us deeper insight or deeper models.

00:13:45.059 --> 00:13:47.659
It's really just talking about the fact that there's

00:13:47.659 --> 00:13:49.580
multiple layers of representation.

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:52.859
A traditional machine learning model might have some feature engineering,

00:13:52.859 --> 00:13:53.979
and then one or two layers.

00:13:53.979 --> 00:13:58.020
A deep learning model could have 20 layers, or 30 layers, or 100 layers.

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:00.419
And so maybe a more accurate term for deep learning

00:14:00.419 --> 00:14:02.619
might be like layered representation learning,

00:14:02.619 --> 00:14:04.859
or hierarchical representation learning.

00:14:04.859 --> 00:14:07.140
The deep learning maybe implies more than it should,

00:14:07.179 --> 00:14:11.219
but it's really just talking about the stacking up of layers.

00:14:11.219 --> 00:14:16.260
And so what has this method achieved?

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:19.619
And you can see from the list here, it's

00:14:19.619 --> 00:14:22.700
done really, really well on a lot of perceptual tasks,

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:26.020
like speech recognition and image classification.

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:28.340
And then those, in turn, have been composed together

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:32.179
to do things like trying to build autonomous driving systems,

00:14:32.179 --> 00:14:35.460
to build reinforcement learning systems that play games.

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:39.219
So it's achieved a lot, this fairly straightforward mechanism.

00:14:39.219 --> 00:14:42.859
And to give you an intuition for why it might be able to do that,

00:14:42.859 --> 00:14:45.500
if you think about a paper ball that's crumpled up,

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:48.940
and you think about trying to write a linear equation for how

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:52.419
to uncrumple the paper ball, it would be really, really difficult to do that.

00:14:52.419 --> 00:14:56.859
But if you decompose the un, it's a really complex geometric transformation

00:14:56.859 --> 00:14:58.140
to uncrumple that whole ball.

00:14:58.140 --> 00:15:02.619
But if you decompose it into a set of simpler geometric transformations,

00:15:02.619 --> 00:15:05.099
i.e. layers, then it's actually straightforward.

00:15:05.099 --> 00:15:07.140
So a human being might just take that paper ball,

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:10.940
and in 30 or so really simple operations, uncrumple it.

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:12.940
And that's really how deep learning models work,

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:16.380
is that they learn these simple geometric transformations that

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:20.340
compose together can do very, very complex transformations,

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:23.239
and therefore solve very complex functions,

00:15:23.239 --> 00:15:26.340
or fit very complex functions.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:28.059
So why should we care about this?

00:15:28.059 --> 00:15:30.979
I actually think the domains that deep learning

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:34.659
is proven to perform well in are ones that are not

00:15:34.659 --> 00:15:37.340
often of interest to R users.

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:41.700
So these perceptual tasks, like vision and speech recognition,

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:43.820
and these reinforcement learning applications,

00:15:43.820 --> 00:15:47.380
they're not things that most R users are concerned with.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:49.859
So it may be that as an R user, you think

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:53.460
it's cool that you can now do state of the art computer vision from R.

00:15:53.460 --> 00:15:56.219
But it's probably more interesting to say,

00:15:56.219 --> 00:16:00.380
does deep learning provide improvements on the techniques

00:16:00.380 --> 00:16:02.539
we have for our traditional domains?

00:16:02.539 --> 00:16:07.059
And is there data that we analyze that has very complex sequence

00:16:07.059 --> 00:16:09.580
or spatial dependencies that's hard to model

00:16:09.580 --> 00:16:11.700
with traditional modeling techniques?

00:16:11.700 --> 00:16:15.500
Is there data that requires a huge amount of feature engineering

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:18.340
that's potentially brittle to model effectively?

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:22.260
So I think it's more interesting to think about,

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:24.760
is deep learning applicable, and how, and when,

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:26.340
to the things that we traditionally do?

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:28.960
And I'll get into some examples of that in a little bit.

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:31.280
But I think it's important to note that it's definitely

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:34.559
proven to be effective at these perceptual tasks.

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:38.080
But it's not yet proven that it's of widespread benefit in other domains,

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:41.400
although certainly people are working hard at it.

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:43.440
So I want to talk a little bit about the mechanism

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:45.359
of how these models are trained, what happens,

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:47.960
and try to convince you that this is actually

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:49.880
a pretty simple and straightforward mechanism.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:51.840
And it's actually kind of surprising that it's

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:54.119
able to solve the kind of problems that it solves.

00:16:54.119 --> 00:16:57.039
So I'll start with a little bit of the basics of how machine learning

00:16:57.039 --> 00:16:59.559
algorithms work, and then give you an example

00:16:59.559 --> 00:17:03.039
of kind of how the training loop for a deep learning model works.

00:17:03.039 --> 00:17:07.640
So just to define some terms, the way machine learning algorithms typically

00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:10.079
work is that you start out with a bunch of data.

00:17:10.079 --> 00:17:12.479
You have x, and you have a known y.

00:17:12.479 --> 00:17:15.959
And you basically just feed batches of that data into the model.

00:17:15.959 --> 00:17:20.599
And the model basically incrementally improves its coefficients

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:24.119
by examining the prediction, saying how close was the prediction

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:27.439
to the actual value, and then adjusting the weights.

00:17:27.439 --> 00:17:31.439
And the training process is a sort of iterative training process

00:17:31.439 --> 00:17:34.319
that takes advantage of a loss function to evaluate the model

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:35.479
and then tweak it over time.

00:17:35.479 --> 00:17:38.199
That's kind of how they work.

00:17:38.199 --> 00:17:40.680
There's significant kind of differences in orientation

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:42.719
between statistical modeling and machine learning.

00:17:42.719 --> 00:17:44.520
I'm not going to go into a lot of depth about that.

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:46.719
I have some links here for you to take a look at.

00:17:46.719 --> 00:17:49.319
But I think one that you'll notice right away

00:17:49.319 --> 00:17:53.719
is that oftentimes statistics is focused on explanation and understanding.

00:17:53.719 --> 00:17:57.479
It's focused on kind of inferring the process by which data is generated.

00:17:57.479 --> 00:17:59.719
And machine learning really, in a lot of cases,

00:17:59.719 --> 00:18:02.079
is exclusively concerned with efficacy of prediction.

00:18:02.079 --> 00:18:02.760
Can we predict things?

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:05.000
We don't need to explain or understand the phenomena.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.319
We just want to predict it.

00:18:06.319 --> 00:18:08.400
So as you're going to see, these deep learning models

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:09.959
are total black box models.

00:18:09.959 --> 00:18:13.640
They do nothing to help you explain or understand phenomena.

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:15.239
But they work well for prediction.

00:18:15.239 --> 00:18:19.520
So that's kind of where that orientation comes from.

00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:20.959
So let's take a look at a model.

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:23.199
This is actually, and again, I showed this before.

00:18:23.199 --> 00:18:25.000
And I'll get into more detail on this later.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.119
Here's the definition of the layers of a model in R.

00:18:29.119 --> 00:18:31.319
And I'll get into what these are a little bit later.

00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:32.520
But there's different types of layers.

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:33.560
I'm going to compose them together.

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:35.560
And I'm going to hope that I can train this model

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:38.319
to recognize handwritten digits.

00:18:38.319 --> 00:18:41.680
And there's an example of kind of what the model is going to learn throughout.

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:46.479
It's going to learn these filters that help go from an image into a prediction.

00:18:46.479 --> 00:18:48.479
So how does that actually happen?

00:18:48.479 --> 00:18:52.239
So when a deep learning model starts, it

00:18:52.239 --> 00:18:53.800
has all these different layers.

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:55.800
The layers have weights.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:59.119
The weights, interestingly, are randomly initialized.

00:18:59.119 --> 00:19:02.920
So in the model at inception, it literally has random weights.

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:04.839
So the predictions that it makes are garbage,

00:19:04.839 --> 00:19:07.359
because the weights are random.

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:10.560
And so what happens is that input is fed into the model,

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:15.239
and predictions come out that initially are wrong, badly wrong.

00:19:15.239 --> 00:19:17.760
But what happens is that the predictions are measured

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:22.000
against the true known targets with a loss function.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.479
So we get this assessment of how good the predictions were.

00:19:24.479 --> 00:19:26.439
Again, initially, they're quite bad.

00:19:26.439 --> 00:19:31.599
And what then happens is that loss function is used to update the weights.

00:19:31.599 --> 00:19:33.719
And that is the job of an optimizer.

00:19:33.719 --> 00:19:36.400
And again, as I mentioned before, these optimizers

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:40.520
can work with just little batches of data, 128 elements at a time.

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:42.520
They don't require that all the data is in memory.

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:44.439
So we feed the data into the model.

00:19:44.439 --> 00:19:46.439
We find out how bad the prediction is.

00:19:46.439 --> 00:19:48.000
We use that to tweak the weights.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.839
And then we repeat that thousands and thousands of times

00:19:50.839 --> 00:19:54.040
until we have a model that performs in a satisfactory way.

00:19:54.040 --> 00:19:57.400
So the actual mathematical mechanisms that work here

00:19:57.400 --> 00:19:58.560
are really straightforward.

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:01.599
And the basic mechanics of the whole thing are straightforward.

00:20:01.599 --> 00:20:06.239
And this tweet is actually from the creator of the Keras library.

00:20:06.239 --> 00:20:09.760
And he's making the point that there's really

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:12.199
nothing complicated going on here.

00:20:12.199 --> 00:20:14.719
But what happens is that once we take this simple mechanism

00:20:14.719 --> 00:20:18.880
and we scale it up, it ends up looking like magic.

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:23.319
And we return to this geometric interpretation that we had earlier.

00:20:23.319 --> 00:20:27.800
It's basically a mathematical mechanism or machine

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:31.079
for taking really complex manifolds of high dimensional data

00:20:31.079 --> 00:20:33.160
and uncrumpling them.

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:40.760
And the ideas behind this were actually originated 30 years ago.

00:20:40.760 --> 00:20:42.119
We kind of knew about this.

00:20:42.119 --> 00:20:44.359
We've known about this for a long, long time.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:49.760
Until about 2012, it actually didn't work very well in practice.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:53.000
And the trick, the thing that changed, is that it turned out

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:56.920
that we needed to be able to have really, really large models with lots

00:20:56.920 --> 00:21:00.439
of big layers and train them on lots and lots of data.

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:03.280
And so what happened is that GPUs allowed

00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:05.599
us to train much, much larger models.

00:21:05.599 --> 00:21:08.199
And the internet allowed us to collect a lot more data.

00:21:08.199 --> 00:21:11.079
And that's kind of what changed and made deep learning actually work,

00:21:11.119 --> 00:21:16.560
even though, again, it sort of was invented conceptually 30 years ago.

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:18.800
So what do I mean by sufficiently large parametric models?

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:22.239
This model I just showed you, the grayscale digit recognizer,

00:21:22.239 --> 00:21:26.920
that model has about 1.2 million coefficients or weights or parameters.

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:29.520
And that's actually a pretty straight grayscale digit recognition

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:31.959
is a lot easier than a lot of computer vision tasks.

00:21:31.959 --> 00:21:35.199
So this one has 1.2 million parameters.

00:21:35.199 --> 00:21:38.839
A bigger model that can recognize all kinds of everyday objects

00:21:38.839 --> 00:21:43.920
and color images here has about 138 million coefficients or parameters.

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:47.280
So when we say sufficiently large, that's what we're talking about.

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:49.359
We're talking about potentially tens of millions

00:21:49.359 --> 00:21:51.119
of parameters that need to be learned.

00:21:51.119 --> 00:21:55.000
And you can see why these models have very little explanatory or ability

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.920
to help with your understanding, because you're

00:21:56.920 --> 00:22:00.560
going to get 138 million parameters, and how do you interpret that?

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:01.920
So that's what I'm talking about.

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:06.000
And that has made deep learning work very well for computer vision.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.439
And what's happening now is that people are

00:22:09.439 --> 00:22:11.839
beginning to apply it to other areas.

00:22:11.839 --> 00:22:14.280
And so I mentioned natural language processing,

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:18.439
but people are starting to work on deep learning for time series.

00:22:18.439 --> 00:22:20.640
They're doing it for biomedical applications.

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:22.640
They're doing it to create some novel approaches

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:24.520
to prediction in some other domains.

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:26.680
So I want to talk a little bit about those frontiers

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:28.359
and kind of where they stand, and I think

00:22:28.359 --> 00:22:33.920
that illuminates a little bit of what our posture toward this is in R.

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:36.000
So computer vision is kind of the poster child

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:37.920
for what deep learning has accomplished.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:41.400
There's a competition that ran from 2010 to 2017

00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:44.800
called the ImageNet Challenge, where machine learning researchers tried

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:49.880
to build models that would predict what images are.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:53.359
And the images were like dog, cat, table, chair.

00:22:53.359 --> 00:22:55.319
So when they started the competition in 2010,

00:22:55.319 --> 00:22:59.800
no entrants used deep learning, and they had 71.8% prediction accuracy.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:04.160
I believe that was the best model in that year.

00:23:04.160 --> 00:23:07.839
In 2012, the very first team that used deep learning

00:23:07.839 --> 00:23:12.680
entered the competition, and that team beat the rest of the field by 11%.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:16.079
And that basically ignited everybody to start looking

00:23:16.079 --> 00:23:17.719
at deep learning for computer vision.

00:23:17.719 --> 00:23:20.880
And by the time we got to 2017, in a period of seven years,

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:25.560
the accuracy in computer vision went from 71.8% to 97.3%,

00:23:25.560 --> 00:23:26.599
which is phenomenal.

00:23:26.599 --> 00:23:30.959
That, more than anything, got people excited about deep learning.

00:23:30.959 --> 00:23:35.040
And actually, the competition is not going to exist anymore after 2017,

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:38.800
because this particular task is basically considered solved.

00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:42.520
So clearly, it works really well in computer vision and image

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:46.280
classification, and you see a lot of applications for it there.

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:49.920
People are also trying to apply it to natural language processing,

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:54.719
and it's not clear how good these techniques work.

00:23:54.719 --> 00:23:56.880
There's a lot of research going on.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:00.079
The plot on the right shows the percentage

00:24:00.079 --> 00:24:03.920
of papers at computational linguistics conferences

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:06.880
that use deep learning, kind of over the same time frame,

00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:10.760
went from around 35% all the way up to 70%.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:13.319
So again, this could be it's a fad, it's trendy,

00:24:13.319 --> 00:24:15.319
everyone's trying to see what they can find out.

00:24:15.319 --> 00:24:17.520
But if you read this paper that I linked to,

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:20.000
and these slides are going to be available after the talk,

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.560
you'll see that people are making progress in natural language

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:24.239
processing to do different things.

00:24:24.239 --> 00:24:27.760
Clearly, a lot of progress has been made in language translation.

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:29.680
And I know you may have seen this, Google

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:33.760
has a new neural machine translation system that really significantly

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:36.359
beats the previous kind of state-of-the-art phrase-based

00:24:36.359 --> 00:24:39.520
translation, and is approaching human-level language translation.

00:24:39.520 --> 00:24:40.680
So that's language translation, but there's

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:43.479
lots of other things you want to do in natural language processing.

00:24:43.479 --> 00:24:45.920
Again, people are starting to apply deep learning.

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:47.920
There are some interesting early results,

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:52.000
but it's not proven that it's going to completely revolutionize that field.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.719
Similarly, people are looking at really complex time series

00:24:55.719 --> 00:24:57.359
forecasting problems.

00:24:57.359 --> 00:25:01.280
This is a paper that actually uses convolutional neural networks, which

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:03.880
are the same kind of neural networks that are used for images.

00:25:03.880 --> 00:25:07.280
And so it's looking for kind of spatial dependencies

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:09.839
that are invariant across the whole time series.

00:25:09.839 --> 00:25:13.319
So they're trying to use techniques used for computer vision on time series.

00:25:13.319 --> 00:25:16.359
And in this case, the data sets they had in this paper,

00:25:16.359 --> 00:25:19.040
they were able to beat some benchmarks of conventional modeling.

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:21.920
But I have not seen in time series.

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:24.520
Again, it's not all of a sudden revolutionizing the field,

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:26.439
and you should always use deep learning for time series.

00:25:26.439 --> 00:25:27.479
That's on the contrary.

00:25:27.479 --> 00:25:29.520
I think there are certain types of time series

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:31.239
that it might work a lot better for.

00:25:31.239 --> 00:25:34.839
But that's really a matter of exploration and research.

00:25:34.839 --> 00:25:39.199
I have one other time series example of a whole different neural network

00:25:39.199 --> 00:25:43.199
architecture that's used to, in this case, it's forecasting stock prices.

00:25:43.199 --> 00:25:45.479
So there's a bunch of articles like this that you'll find.

00:25:45.479 --> 00:25:47.439
And if you work with a lot of time series data,

00:25:47.439 --> 00:25:49.199
it might be interesting to read these papers

00:25:49.199 --> 00:25:53.680
and see where deep learning is performing well and where it's struggling.

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:57.800
There's a lot of work going on in biomedical applications.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:01.319
And this could be everything from patient treatment, patient classification,

00:26:01.319 --> 00:26:03.479
to actual fundamental biological processes.

00:26:03.479 --> 00:26:06.280
This paper just came out this month.

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:09.520
And it's kind of a roundup of the work that's going on there.

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:12.359
And I think they conclude similarly.

00:26:12.359 --> 00:26:16.160
There's not evidence we're revolutionizing this field or these fields.

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:18.040
But there are promising advances on the state of the art

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:20.959
worth paying attention to.

00:26:20.959 --> 00:26:23.079
This is a very, very interesting example.

00:26:23.079 --> 00:26:25.319
This paper just got published this month.

00:26:25.319 --> 00:26:28.680
And it was a study that was done by Google, Stanford, U of Chicago

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:32.239
School of Medicine, and the University of California, San Francisco.

00:26:32.239 --> 00:26:35.599
And they wanted to see if they could provide better predictions

00:26:35.599 --> 00:26:39.719
about patient outcomes based on electronic health records.

00:26:39.719 --> 00:26:42.000
And so what they pointed out is that typically,

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:45.239
statistical models, electronic health records are really messy.

00:26:45.239 --> 00:26:46.400
They're uneven.

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:49.520
There's different features in different patients.

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:51.599
The data is collected in inconsistent ways.

00:26:51.599 --> 00:26:52.760
They're really messy.

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:55.000
So typically, a huge amount of effort is taken

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:59.520
to select out a bunch of features, clean up and normalize those features,

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:01.880
and then do predictions using conventional machine

00:27:01.880 --> 00:27:03.359
learning or statistical models.

00:27:03.359 --> 00:27:05.520
But what they point out in the paper is that when you do that,

00:27:05.520 --> 00:27:07.680
you're actually discarding a huge amount of data.

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:09.479
All the data that you, all the features you

00:27:09.479 --> 00:27:13.280
excluded because they weren't consistent or coded consistently.

00:27:13.280 --> 00:27:18.079
Things like the handwritten notes of a physician's, it's all thrown out.

00:27:18.079 --> 00:27:19.400
So they said, what if we did this?

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:21.640
What if we build a deep learning model that

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:24.680
considered the entire medical record of every patient,

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:27.319
including the physician's notes, and including

00:27:27.319 --> 00:27:29.839
the fields that are not normalized against each other,

00:27:29.839 --> 00:27:33.719
and see if we could actually beat conventional methods of doing

00:27:33.719 --> 00:27:34.560
prediction.

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:35.839
And in this case, they did find that they

00:27:35.839 --> 00:27:37.760
could beat state of the art statistical models

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:39.680
in a bunch of categories.

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:42.479
I don't think it was necessarily easy to get this result.

00:27:42.479 --> 00:27:45.119
If you look at the paper, Jeff Dean is on the paper.

00:27:45.119 --> 00:27:46.880
He's like the inventor of TensorFlow.

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:47.640
He worked on this.

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:49.880
So I don't know that anybody could just walk in and get

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:51.359
these kind of results.

00:27:51.359 --> 00:27:54.319
But it's interesting that it's possible.

00:27:54.319 --> 00:27:56.880
It's a very, very different approach to prediction.

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:00.079
It's basically saying that the feature normalization and feature

00:28:00.079 --> 00:28:03.160
extraction is going to be done by the layers of the deep learning model,

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:06.800
not by kind of human reasoning about the data

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:09.000
and human composition of like a sensible model.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.839
We're just going to learn what the model is.

00:28:10.839 --> 00:28:12.760
So this is a really interesting paper to read.

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:16.839
Again, this just came out in the last, I think, couple weeks.

00:28:16.839 --> 00:28:19.319
There are quite a few problems with deep learning models.

00:28:19.319 --> 00:28:21.479
I've alluded to some of these already.

00:28:21.479 --> 00:28:24.800
The fact that they're black boxes and you can't interpret them

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:27.199
excludes their utility for a whole bunch of things

00:28:27.199 --> 00:28:33.160
that we want to do with statistics and machine learning and R.

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:34.640
They can be brittle.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:39.119
So if you look up adversarial examples, there's a really classic one

00:28:39.119 --> 00:28:41.239
where you see like two pictures of a panda.

00:28:41.239 --> 00:28:43.959
And to the human eye, they look completely the same.

00:28:43.959 --> 00:28:47.520
But one panda has been like tweaked in really subtle ways

00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:51.319
to force the model to have a totally different prediction.

00:28:51.319 --> 00:28:54.439
So people are trying to overcome adversarial examples

00:28:54.439 --> 00:28:55.479
with various techniques.

00:28:55.479 --> 00:28:56.520
But it's just important.

00:28:56.520 --> 00:28:58.439
A human being can look at a panda and it just

00:28:58.439 --> 00:29:01.479
knows there's something way, way, way more complex going on

00:29:01.479 --> 00:29:03.839
for a human being perceptual task.

00:29:03.839 --> 00:29:07.599
These models work, but then they're brittle.

00:29:07.599 --> 00:29:10.640
They typically need a large amount of data to perform well.

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:13.719
Like I said, we've known about deep neural networks for 30 years.

00:29:13.719 --> 00:29:15.680
And they didn't really work very well until now.

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:17.180
So they typically need a lot of data.

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:19.040
Although there are ways to transfer knowledge

00:29:19.040 --> 00:29:22.160
from a model built on larger amounts of data

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:24.319
to a model that's trained on smaller amounts of data.

00:29:24.319 --> 00:29:27.319
So there are ways to use deep learning for smaller data sets.

00:29:27.319 --> 00:29:29.199
But they typically need a lot of data.

00:29:29.199 --> 00:29:32.280
And they're very computationally expensive to train as well.

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:35.000
So this creates another problem, which I think

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.199
is going to get worse and be annoying to all of us,

00:29:39.199 --> 00:29:41.520
which is that there's a lot of hype about deep learning.

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:43.719
There's actually a lot of hype about AI,

00:29:43.719 --> 00:29:47.680
which as far as I can tell means I have an if-then statement.

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:48.479
So it's AI.

00:29:48.479 --> 00:29:52.479
You know, it's awful.

00:29:52.479 --> 00:29:56.199
And unfortunately, the current tools

00:29:56.199 --> 00:29:59.199
for doing deep learning models have become so good

00:29:59.199 --> 00:30:02.359
that software engineers or even laypeople

00:30:02.359 --> 00:30:04.479
with no training in modeling or statistics

00:30:04.479 --> 00:30:06.119
can actually build these models.

00:30:06.119 --> 00:30:07.400
And they'll actually think that they've

00:30:07.400 --> 00:30:08.599
built a model that's really great.

00:30:08.599 --> 00:30:10.560
They'll say, oh, look, I've got 84% accuracy.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:11.359
I built this model.

00:30:11.359 --> 00:30:12.400
I know nothing about modeling.

00:30:12.400 --> 00:30:13.439
I know nothing about statistics.

00:30:13.439 --> 00:30:14.819
I know nothing about probability.

00:30:14.819 --> 00:30:15.719
But here's a model.

00:30:15.719 --> 00:30:16.680
And it's deep.

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:20.359
So it's obviously better than whatever anybody else has.

00:30:20.359 --> 00:30:23.680
But typically, you can't actually

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:26.560
outperform traditional statistical modeling techniques

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:27.680
without a lot of effort.

00:30:27.680 --> 00:30:29.060
So usually these models are going

00:30:29.060 --> 00:30:31.400
to be bad compared to the models that we build.

00:30:31.400 --> 00:30:33.319
And so we're going to have to deal with this.

00:30:33.319 --> 00:30:35.479
We're going to have to patiently explain why, well,

00:30:35.479 --> 00:30:38.160
maybe that model isn't the best one for us to use.

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:40.520
I don't think this is reason for us to throw up our hands

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:42.719
and say, we don't want anything to do with this.

00:30:42.719 --> 00:30:44.359
I think what we need to do is promote

00:30:44.359 --> 00:30:46.560
a more balanced and knowledgeable and nuanced

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:48.400
dialogue about what these things are good for

00:30:48.400 --> 00:30:50.040
and what they're not good for.

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:52.479
Because in spite of these problems,

00:30:52.479 --> 00:30:54.280
it does a lot of really useful things.

00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:55.680
You can actually, this is a slide

00:30:55.680 --> 00:31:00.800
that Google uses that shows how many model description

00:31:00.800 --> 00:31:03.040
files, which are basically TensorFlow models,

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:05.239
are sitting in repositories all over Google.

00:31:05.239 --> 00:31:07.760
And you can see, since the release of TensorFlow,

00:31:07.760 --> 00:31:09.800
that has really accelerated across all areas

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:10.400
of the company.

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:12.599
So these models, in spite of their problems,

00:31:12.599 --> 00:31:15.079
their brittleness, their black box nature,

00:31:15.079 --> 00:31:16.719
can do super useful things.

00:31:16.719 --> 00:31:18.880
So we want to figure out what useful things they

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:21.719
can do for us in R. And that kind of brings me

00:31:21.719 --> 00:31:26.359
to what we've done in R to let you use TensorFlow.

00:31:26.359 --> 00:31:28.839
And we actually have a bunch of different interfaces,

00:31:28.839 --> 00:31:29.900
high level and low level.

00:31:29.900 --> 00:31:31.400
We have some tools that help you be

00:31:31.400 --> 00:31:33.640
more productive with your workflow

00:31:33.640 --> 00:31:35.560
and managing experiments, ways for you

00:31:35.560 --> 00:31:38.040
to easily use GPUs for training, and then hopefully

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:41.280
an adequate amount of learning resources

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:44.239
so that you can better understand how to use

00:31:44.239 --> 00:31:45.599
these tools in your own work.

00:31:45.599 --> 00:31:49.640
So top level, we actually have three different APIs

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:51.280
for TensorFlow.

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:52.920
One is the Keras API, which I'm going

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:54.000
to talk quite a bit about.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:55.599
That's a very high level interface

00:31:55.599 --> 00:31:57.000
for defining neural networks.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:58.619
The R code that I've showed you so far

00:31:58.619 --> 00:32:00.680
has been from the Keras API.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:02.640
There's another API called the Estimator API,

00:32:02.640 --> 00:32:07.160
which does more classic classifiers, regressors,

00:32:07.160 --> 00:32:09.640
support vector machines, random forests,

00:32:09.640 --> 00:32:11.800
kind of classic statistical machine learning

00:32:11.800 --> 00:32:13.959
models for TensorFlow.

00:32:13.959 --> 00:32:16.439
And then the Core API is actually what Greta used.

00:32:16.439 --> 00:32:19.239
This gives you full access to the entire computational graph.

00:32:19.239 --> 00:32:22.040
It's really good for library builders,

00:32:22.040 --> 00:32:23.359
so not something I'm going to talk about.

00:32:23.359 --> 00:32:25.619
I'm actually not going to talk about the Estimator API

00:32:25.619 --> 00:32:27.479
or the Core API much at all.

00:32:27.479 --> 00:32:29.719
This maps out into a suite of, today,

00:32:29.719 --> 00:32:31.560
seven different R packages.

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:34.719
Three for the interface to TensorFlow.

00:32:34.719 --> 00:32:38.400
There's a package for working with large data

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:40.239
sets called tf.datasets.

00:32:40.239 --> 00:32:42.680
And then there's packages, as I said, supporting tools

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:44.920
for deployment, for managing experiments,

00:32:44.920 --> 00:32:46.839
and then for interfacing with Google Cloud ML.

00:32:46.839 --> 00:32:49.479
And I'll talk about those supporting tools

00:32:49.479 --> 00:32:52.119
in a little bit.

00:32:52.119 --> 00:32:53.599
So I've shown you this code before.

00:32:53.599 --> 00:32:56.280
This is the Keras API, high level API for neural networks.

00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:59.439
And I will go into a lot more detail about that in a minute.

00:32:59.439 --> 00:33:01.760
The Estimator API gives you these high level.

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:04.839
These almost look like regular R modeling functions,

00:33:04.839 --> 00:33:05.599
really high level.

00:33:05.599 --> 00:33:08.079
Say do a regression, do a classification.

00:33:08.079 --> 00:33:09.920
That's what Estimators is about.

00:33:09.920 --> 00:33:12.359
And then the Core API is you interacting directly

00:33:12.359 --> 00:33:13.400
with the graph.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:16.719
Here you can see I'm building the loss function manually,

00:33:16.719 --> 00:33:18.959
and I'm manually doing the training loop.

00:33:18.959 --> 00:33:21.680
So I don't recommend people use this API

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:25.280
unless you're actually trying to build tools for other people

00:33:25.280 --> 00:33:27.719
or do some novel, like Greta, do something

00:33:27.719 --> 00:33:29.760
novel with TensorFlow for R.

00:33:29.760 --> 00:33:31.400
So let's talk a little bit about Keras.

00:33:31.400 --> 00:33:32.760
I'll give you an example and talk

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:36.520
about the different components of the Keras API.

00:33:36.520 --> 00:33:40.400
I wanted to make a little bit of a note about why Keras.

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:44.119
And actually, Keras is being, at this point,

00:33:44.119 --> 00:33:45.599
especially over the last six months,

00:33:45.599 --> 00:33:48.599
is being promoted by Google as kind of the preferred

00:33:48.599 --> 00:33:51.040
interface to TensorFlow.

00:33:51.040 --> 00:33:54.400
Keras works great for end user applications.

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:57.760
You can see this on the left is the Google search

00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:02.319
for deep learning frameworks over the last three or four

00:34:02.319 --> 00:34:03.079
years.

00:34:03.079 --> 00:34:04.959
And you can see that both TensorFlow and Keras

00:34:04.959 --> 00:34:06.800
are pulling away from other frameworks.

00:34:06.800 --> 00:34:08.219
And on the right, you can actually

00:34:08.219 --> 00:34:10.560
see the use citation of deep learning frameworks

00:34:10.560 --> 00:34:12.320
in research papers.

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:15.000
And you can see while TensorFlow has the most citations,

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.280
Keras, even though it's really great, high level,

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.919
easy to use API, is also used quite a bit in research.

00:34:19.919 --> 00:34:24.199
So you can go pretty deep with Keras as well.

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:28.360
I want to walk through what Keras code in R looks like.

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:30.439
And this is using that MNIST example, again,

00:34:30.439 --> 00:34:33.919
of handwritten digit recognition.

00:34:33.919 --> 00:34:36.360
The first thing we do is data preprocessing.

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:39.919
And this really just has to do with reshaping and scaling data

00:34:39.919 --> 00:34:41.879
into tensors.

00:34:41.879 --> 00:34:43.520
You're almost always going to be dealing

00:34:43.520 --> 00:34:45.399
with, a lot of times, R matrices.

00:34:45.399 --> 00:34:47.239
But you're going to get your data off of disk

00:34:47.239 --> 00:34:49.540
or off of whatever, from a data frame,

00:34:49.540 --> 00:34:51.239
and you're going to turn it into tensors.

00:34:51.239 --> 00:34:53.959
So that's a deep preprocessing step.

00:34:53.959 --> 00:34:56.199
And then you're going to define your model.

00:34:56.199 --> 00:34:57.580
So I've shown this before.

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:59.040
This is the definition of a model,

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:00.739
which basically says, what are my layers,

00:35:00.739 --> 00:35:03.639
and how are they going to behave?

00:35:03.639 --> 00:35:06.320
So that's the model definition.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:08.879
And then you're going to compile the model, which basically

00:35:08.879 --> 00:35:11.120
says, what's the loss function and optimizer

00:35:11.120 --> 00:35:12.879
that I want to use during training?

00:35:12.879 --> 00:35:15.080
And what metrics do I want to collect during training?

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:18.479
So this is really the heart of making a Keras model.

00:35:18.479 --> 00:35:20.320
Define the layers and compile it.

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:23.719
I want to make a quick note about this second statement

00:35:23.719 --> 00:35:25.399
here, model compile.

00:35:25.399 --> 00:35:30.239
You'll notice I do not assign the result of that expression

00:35:30.239 --> 00:35:31.120
back to the model.

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:34.439
I'm actually modifying the model in place.

00:35:34.439 --> 00:35:36.239
That's not conventional in R. Typically,

00:35:36.239 --> 00:35:38.280
in R, objects are by value.

00:35:38.280 --> 00:35:40.760
You modify the object, and then you return a copy of it

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:42.239
that has the modifications.

00:35:42.239 --> 00:35:46.439
But Keras models are these acyclic graphs of layers.

00:35:46.439 --> 00:35:47.260
They are stateful.

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:49.000
They get updated during training.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.159
I haven't shown this yet, but a layer can actually

00:35:51.159 --> 00:35:53.399
be repeated at multiple places within the model.

00:35:53.399 --> 00:35:55.840
So these Keras models are by reference objects.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:35:58.399
And so the code you'll see when we mutate them,

00:35:58.399 --> 00:36:03.120
when we compile them or fit them, it's all done in place.

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:04.540
I just wanted to make that clear,

00:36:04.540 --> 00:36:06.120
because I think when you see this code,

00:36:06.120 --> 00:36:09.760
it's different from maybe other R code that you've seen.

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:10.879
So now training.

00:36:10.879 --> 00:36:14.000
The training process is done through the fit function.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:15.860
And we basically say, here's our data.

00:36:15.860 --> 00:36:17.399
And in this case, we're saying we're

00:36:17.399 --> 00:36:19.520
going to do 128 samples at a time to the model.

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:20.939
We might have millions of samples.

00:36:20.939 --> 00:36:23.439
We'll just do 120 at a time.

00:36:23.439 --> 00:36:25.500
We want to traverse the input data set 10 times.

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:27.000
That's what epochs is.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:30.479
Again, since we're going to iteratively learn on batches,

00:36:30.479 --> 00:36:32.199
it's not enough to see the data once.

00:36:32.199 --> 00:36:33.879
We're going to see it multiple times.

00:36:33.879 --> 00:36:35.800
And then as we're fitting, we're going

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:39.320
to hold out 20% of the data and use that to validate that we're

00:36:39.320 --> 00:36:41.439
not just overfitting to our data set.

00:36:41.439 --> 00:36:43.760
We're not basically a deep learning model can actually

00:36:43.760 --> 00:36:45.000
just memorize the data.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:46.840
And so it's giving you a function that really

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:49.360
isn't useful because all it's done is memorize the data set.

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:50.199
So we hold out data.

00:36:50.199 --> 00:36:52.760
And we test it against that to make sure we're not just

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:54.399
merely memorizing data.

00:36:54.399 --> 00:36:56.239
So that's what training looks like.

00:36:56.239 --> 00:36:57.699
When we're done with training, you

00:36:57.699 --> 00:37:00.360
can see we assign back to a history object.

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:03.840
And we can plot the history and see how the training proceeded

00:37:03.840 --> 00:37:06.639
and how our accuracy and loss improved or didn't

00:37:06.639 --> 00:37:09.439
improve during training.

00:37:09.439 --> 00:37:11.080
Later, we can evaluate the model,

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:14.560
which is taking yet another set of data that we've held out,

00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:16.600
making sure the model has never seen this data.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:19.280
And then we test to see how good the predictions are.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:21.280
Was the model really an overfit to the data?

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:22.840
Or does it generalize well?

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:26.040
And then we can use predict or predict classes

00:37:26.040 --> 00:37:28.159
to actually generate predictions from the model.

00:37:28.159 --> 00:37:30.280
So I actually want to show you a little bit of what

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:32.199
that looks like in our studio.

00:37:32.199 --> 00:37:35.239
This is a complete end-to-end script

00:37:35.239 --> 00:37:37.560
that I just showed you in slides.

00:37:37.560 --> 00:37:41.560
So again, when we start, we'll load the data.

00:37:41.560 --> 00:37:44.399
The MNIST data set's actually built into Keras.

00:37:44.399 --> 00:37:46.040
So I get the raw data in.

00:37:46.040 --> 00:37:49.439
And then I'm going to turn that data into some matrices

00:37:49.439 --> 00:37:51.439
that I'm going to be able to feed into the model.

00:37:51.439 --> 00:37:53.520
You can see on the side now I've reshaped the data

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.239
into a bunch of matrices.

00:37:56.239 --> 00:37:59.199
And then I define the model.

00:37:59.199 --> 00:38:01.080
And then I compile the model.

00:38:01.080 --> 00:38:02.679
I can print a summary of the model

00:38:02.679 --> 00:38:04.979
to see how many parameters I have, what the layers are,

00:38:04.979 --> 00:38:05.800
and how they work.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:07.399
And finally, I fit the model.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:11.719
And as the model's being fit, we're

00:38:11.719 --> 00:38:13.639
going to actually show you the training metrics

00:38:13.639 --> 00:38:15.320
in real time in our studio.

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:16.860
And this is actually extremely useful

00:38:16.860 --> 00:38:18.879
because a lot of times when you fit a model,

00:38:18.879 --> 00:38:21.040
you're overfitting, your accuracy is not improving,

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:22.159
the model doesn't work.

00:38:22.159 --> 00:38:24.840
And it's really good to be able to visualize that as you fit it

00:38:24.840 --> 00:38:27.239
so then you can stop training and say, nope,

00:38:27.239 --> 00:38:29.919
that architecture doesn't work, those hyperparameters don't

00:38:29.919 --> 00:38:32.760
work, I need to try to do something else.

00:38:32.760 --> 00:38:35.439
I can also plot the history.

00:38:35.439 --> 00:38:38.040
And you can actually get at the data frame behind that

00:38:38.040 --> 00:38:40.719
if you want to do various types of custom visualizations

00:38:40.719 --> 00:38:42.280
of your training history.

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:44.800
Evaluate to see what my accuracy looks like on data

00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:47.000
I haven't seen before, and then generate predictions.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:48.800
So that's just the basic mechanic.

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:51.919
Models can get more complicated, but some Keras scripts

00:38:51.919 --> 00:38:53.199
are really this simple.

00:38:53.199 --> 00:38:54.159
This is all you do.

00:38:54.159 --> 00:38:56.959
Not to say that the task of actually designing and building

00:38:56.959 --> 00:38:58.679
and getting the model to work is simple.

00:38:58.679 --> 00:39:01.760
A lot of times, that takes a huge amount of iteration.

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:05.979
So layers is kind of the core construct in Keras.

00:39:05.979 --> 00:39:08.060
And there's actually 65 different layers available,

00:39:08.060 --> 00:39:10.399
and you can create your own layers.

00:39:10.399 --> 00:39:12.060
This is just a sampling of some of them.

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:13.760
I'm going to talk categorically about some

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:16.879
of the types of layers that there are.

00:39:16.879 --> 00:39:18.560
There's dense layers, which are kind

00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:20.080
of the staple of neural networks.

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:23.479
These work the same way that traditional neural networks that

00:39:23.479 --> 00:39:27.080
were written about and used in the 70s work.

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:31.419
And they're kind of a staple of every deep learning model.

00:39:31.419 --> 00:39:33.500
Usually, if you're using more sophisticated layers

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:36.080
at the end of the model, you'll have these dense layers.

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:37.659
And these dense layers are really just

00:39:37.659 --> 00:39:39.399
a bunch of weights and biases that

00:39:39.399 --> 00:39:44.239
are applied and cascade through other dense layers.

00:39:44.239 --> 00:39:48.120
Convolutional layers are used for computer vision,

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:49.199
most commonly.

00:39:49.199 --> 00:39:54.199
And they're basically trying to find spatial features.

00:39:54.199 --> 00:39:56.639
And they're trying to find spatial features that,

00:39:56.639 --> 00:39:58.800
when they learn, like, for example, what an edge is

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:02.280
or what an eyeball is, that knowledge

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:05.199
is actually transferable to other parts of the image.

00:40:05.199 --> 00:40:07.959
So if I see an eye in a certain quadrant of the image,

00:40:07.959 --> 00:40:10.239
and then I see later on an eye in another quadrant,

00:40:10.239 --> 00:40:12.040
I can still recognize that as an eye.

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:13.280
So the reason it's convolutional is

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:16.080
we're building up these filters that recognize patterns.

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:18.760
And then we're convolving, sliding the filter

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:21.320
across the entire image.

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:23.239
And you can see an example of that here.

00:40:23.239 --> 00:40:26.679
So again, there's much better explanations

00:40:26.679 --> 00:40:27.560
for how this works.

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:29.260
But you can think of convolutional layers

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:30.879
as really good for image processing,

00:40:30.879 --> 00:40:33.280
spatial dependencies, that sort of thing.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:36.060
Recurrent layers are basically layers

00:40:36.100 --> 00:40:38.379
that have some memory or state.

00:40:38.379 --> 00:40:39.939
And so if you're dealing with sequence data,

00:40:39.939 --> 00:40:42.139
like time series data or text,

00:40:42.139 --> 00:40:44.919
where it matters not only what I'm seeing now,

00:40:44.919 --> 00:40:46.419
but what I've seen in the past,

00:40:46.419 --> 00:40:48.159
recurrent layers are able to maintain state.

00:40:48.159 --> 00:40:49.399
So they're oftentimes used

00:40:49.399 --> 00:40:51.899
in these sequence-oriented applications.

00:40:51.899 --> 00:40:53.340
And then embedding layers,

00:40:53.340 --> 00:40:55.820
for those of you who do natural language processing,

00:40:55.820 --> 00:40:58.820
is a way of vectorizing text.

00:40:58.820 --> 00:41:01.179
So one way to vectorize text would be to say,

00:41:01.179 --> 00:41:03.260
I've got an instance of the word cat,

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:06.020
an instance of the word dog, and they're just classes.

00:41:06.020 --> 00:41:07.419
It's just cat versus dog.

00:41:07.419 --> 00:41:08.820
But another way would be,

00:41:08.820 --> 00:41:10.860
I've got a vector that represents

00:41:10.860 --> 00:41:12.820
semantic relationships between words.

00:41:12.820 --> 00:41:15.300
So in one of the dimensions of that,

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:17.540
one of the axes of that vector,

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:18.699
I've got a thing that says,

00:41:18.699 --> 00:41:20.820
oh, cat and dog are both animals.

00:41:20.820 --> 00:41:25.659
So embedding layers do this kind of vectorization.

00:41:25.659 --> 00:41:28.739
And you can actually learn the embedding jointly

00:41:28.739 --> 00:41:30.139
with building the model,

00:41:30.139 --> 00:41:32.399
or you can load a pre-trained word embedding

00:41:32.399 --> 00:41:34.340
that we conventionally use, like word2vec.

00:41:34.340 --> 00:41:35.560
You can load one of those embeddings

00:41:35.560 --> 00:41:37.000
into an embedding layer.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.580
So there's just a few of the layer types,

00:41:39.580 --> 00:41:40.860
but again, there's 65 layers.

00:41:40.860 --> 00:41:43.300
And a lot of what doing deep learning is

00:41:43.300 --> 00:41:45.280
is trying to figure out what is the right composition

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:46.899
of those layers and behavior of those layers

00:41:46.899 --> 00:41:49.000
to get a model that works well.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:52.580
So in Keras, once we define our layers,

00:41:52.580 --> 00:41:55.219
we compile the model, and what is that really?

00:41:55.219 --> 00:41:57.500
The compilation of a model is really converting the layers

00:41:57.500 --> 00:41:58.979
into a TensorFlow graph,

00:41:58.979 --> 00:42:02.520
and then applying the loss function and optimizer to those.

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:05.520
That's what compile, the compile step really does.

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:08.879
There are a wide variety of loss functions

00:42:08.879 --> 00:42:10.060
available in Keras,

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:11.760
and you can actually write your own loss functions.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:13.040
So depending on what you're doing,

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:14.719
you'll use maybe a custom loss

00:42:14.719 --> 00:42:15.879
or maybe one of the built-in losses

00:42:15.879 --> 00:42:18.479
or more than one of the built-in losses.

00:42:18.479 --> 00:42:20.479
There are many optimizers that are built in.

00:42:20.479 --> 00:42:22.000
Again, these optimizers don't require

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.479
that all the memory is in RAM.

00:42:24.360 --> 00:42:26.360
There are many metrics built in,

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:28.080
and you can write your own metrics.

00:42:28.080 --> 00:42:30.879
So these are ways of assessing how the model is training,

00:42:30.879 --> 00:42:32.879
how it's behaving, how well it's doing.

00:42:34.639 --> 00:42:37.399
All of this is summarized in a cheat sheet that we have.

00:42:37.399 --> 00:42:39.320
Don't worry about copying this URL down

00:42:39.320 --> 00:42:41.199
because I'm going to share the link to these slides,

00:42:41.199 --> 00:42:43.280
and this is available from the TensorFlow for our website,

00:42:43.280 --> 00:42:45.080
but this cheat sheet kind of goes through

00:42:45.080 --> 00:42:46.780
a lot of the same content that I just went through,

00:42:46.780 --> 00:42:49.719
but I think it actually is a much more clear treatment.

00:42:49.719 --> 00:42:50.879
It's really excellent.

00:42:51.879 --> 00:42:55.280
So I wanted to go on and talk about some examples

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:59.719
that we've written up of using the R Keras API

00:42:59.719 --> 00:43:01.080
to do deep learning.

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:04.320
These are all available on this gallery page

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:06.320
of our TensorFlow for our website,

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:08.199
and each one of these is a blog post

00:43:08.199 --> 00:43:10.600
that writes up in detail kind of the motivation,

00:43:10.600 --> 00:43:12.719
what we did, what worked, what didn't work,

00:43:12.719 --> 00:43:14.520
intermediate data visualizations.

00:43:14.520 --> 00:43:18.040
So a really good way of exploring these different use cases.

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:22.000
The first one actually demonstrates how to do

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:23.760
what I mentioned earlier, transfer learning,

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:27.320
where you, here we're basically going to try to predict

00:43:27.320 --> 00:43:29.080
whether an image is a cat or a dog,

00:43:29.159 --> 00:43:32.120
and we're only gonna train on 2,000 input images,

00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:34.399
and the way that's gonna work is that we're gonna use

00:43:34.399 --> 00:43:38.959
a model that was already built, that knows about edges

00:43:38.959 --> 00:43:42.800
and things related to identifying things like cats and dogs,

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:44.919
and we're gonna transfer the knowledge of that model

00:43:44.919 --> 00:43:46.000
into our new model.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.080
So this is an example of using deep learning

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:49.439
with a smaller data set.

00:43:50.479 --> 00:43:52.320
There's another example that talks about

00:43:52.320 --> 00:43:56.280
time series forecasting of weather, temperature data,

00:43:56.280 --> 00:43:58.479
and it talks about different techniques

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.600
for different things you can try

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:04.399
to make a time series model perform better,

00:44:04.399 --> 00:44:07.879
including stacking up multiple recurrent layers together

00:44:07.879 --> 00:44:09.159
by directional recurrent layers,

00:44:09.159 --> 00:44:12.760
which look at both temporal orders of data.

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:14.959
So this is a good kind of introductory primer

00:44:14.959 --> 00:44:17.120
to doing time series.

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:19.760
There's a really cool example we have

00:44:19.760 --> 00:44:24.360
where we're trying to, for cancer immunotherapy,

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:28.080
classify peptides to figure out how they're gonna bind,

00:44:28.479 --> 00:44:31.320
if they're reintroduced, and this is using deep learning.

00:44:31.320 --> 00:44:35.159
We show the same classification task with a random forest

00:44:35.159 --> 00:44:37.479
and with a simple feed-forward neural network,

00:44:37.479 --> 00:44:38.919
and it's a really good introduction

00:44:38.919 --> 00:44:41.840
to how you might use deep learning with this sort of data.

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:46.280
Another example is looking for credit card fraud,

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:47.840
and what's interesting about this is that you've got,

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:50.600
I think, something like half a million transactions,

00:44:50.600 --> 00:44:54.479
and only 2,000 of the transactions are fraudulent.

00:44:54.479 --> 00:44:57.360
So this is a way of trying to find signal

00:44:57.360 --> 00:45:01.120
in those 2,000 examples of fraudulent transactions

00:45:01.120 --> 00:45:06.000
and be able to still get good predictive accuracy,

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:08.760
even though we don't have that much data to train on.

00:45:08.760 --> 00:45:10.520
So that's what that is.

00:45:11.479 --> 00:45:14.280
This is a text classification example,

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.679
which says we've got questions from Quora.

00:45:16.679 --> 00:45:18.919
Are they duplicates or not?

00:45:18.919 --> 00:45:20.800
It's based on a Kaggle dataset.

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:22.040
One of the interesting things about this,

00:45:22.040 --> 00:45:24.919
we also show how to create a shiny application

00:45:24.919 --> 00:45:27.040
that's a front-end for this model.

00:45:27.719 --> 00:45:28.560
It's actually quite straightforward to do that,

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:30.280
and this gives you a sort of simple introduction

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:31.120
to doing that.

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:34.919
Another example is using deep learning

00:45:34.919 --> 00:45:36.479
to predict customer churn,

00:45:36.479 --> 00:45:37.719
and this also demonstrates

00:45:37.719 --> 00:45:38.840
a couple other interesting things,

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:40.439
one of which is the LIME package,

00:45:40.439 --> 00:45:42.040
which I'll talk about in a minute,

00:45:42.040 --> 00:45:43.419
which is a way of,

00:45:43.419 --> 00:45:45.959
it's not a way to understand how the model works,

00:45:45.959 --> 00:45:49.199
but it's a way to understand for an individual prediction

00:45:49.199 --> 00:45:52.479
what features contributed to that prediction.

00:45:52.479 --> 00:45:54.320
So that LIME package is demonstrated here,

00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:56.439
and we also demonstrate, again,

00:45:56.439 --> 00:45:57.639
building a shiny application

00:45:57.639 --> 00:45:59.239
on top of a deep learning model.

00:46:00.639 --> 00:46:03.639
Another example is learning word embeddings

00:46:03.639 --> 00:46:04.639
from Amazon Reviews.

00:46:04.639 --> 00:46:05.879
So this is, we've got,

00:46:05.879 --> 00:46:09.000
I think these are the Fine Food Reviews dataset from Amazon,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:09.959
and we're trying to figure out

00:46:09.959 --> 00:46:12.360
what words are semantically similar.

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:13.959
So this is just a plot of some of the,

00:46:13.959 --> 00:46:17.080
it ends up being a multidimensional embedding,

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:20.280
but this is an example of doing word embeddings.

00:46:22.560 --> 00:46:25.719
Couple examples about addressing explainability,

00:46:25.719 --> 00:46:29.199
because again, while 138 million parameter model,

00:46:29.199 --> 00:46:32.919
looking at it doesn't tell you anything about the phenomena,

00:46:32.919 --> 00:46:35.159
it is actually possible oftentimes to understand

00:46:35.159 --> 00:46:38.879
why a given prediction was made by a neural network.

00:46:38.879 --> 00:46:40.239
Here's an example of,

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:42.879
we're classifying images,

00:46:42.879 --> 00:46:46.159
and we've predicted that this image is an African elephant,

00:46:46.159 --> 00:46:48.020
and actually by inspecting the gradients

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:49.399
of the intermediate layers,

00:46:49.399 --> 00:46:52.280
it's possible to pull out a heat map that says,

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:54.040
these are the parts of the image

00:46:54.439 --> 00:46:57.919
that most caused us to do this classification.

00:46:57.919 --> 00:47:00.000
So then we juxtapose the heat map over the original image,

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.719
and we actually see, this is why the model,

00:47:02.719 --> 00:47:04.199
these are the things that contributed to the model

00:47:04.199 --> 00:47:06.040
saying that this was an African elephant.

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:08.239
And then similarly LIME,

00:47:08.239 --> 00:47:10.639
which allows you to take an individual prediction

00:47:10.639 --> 00:47:14.520
and say what features contributed to that prediction.

00:47:14.520 --> 00:47:18.360
So there is work going on in explainability of predictions,

00:47:18.360 --> 00:47:20.239
it's not the same thing as I look at the model

00:47:20.239 --> 00:47:21.800
and it explains the phenomena,

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:23.679
but a lot of these models are gonna be used

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:25.600
if they're being used for things like patient care

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:28.280
or making recommendations about surgical procedures

00:47:28.280 --> 00:47:31.479
or approving or denying loans,

00:47:31.479 --> 00:47:32.560
they have to be explainable.

00:47:32.560 --> 00:47:33.800
We have to be able to say,

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:35.560
we have a machine learning algorithm,

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:37.760
but this is why the machine learning algorithm

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:39.320
is coming out the way it is.

00:47:40.239 --> 00:47:44.520
So kind of coming back to this idea of frontiers,

00:47:45.439 --> 00:47:47.280
many fields have a deep learning frontier

00:47:47.280 --> 00:47:50.879
that is not yet reached or even well approached,

00:47:50.879 --> 00:47:52.919
and in most of these cases,

00:47:53.159 --> 00:47:54.719
the traditional statistical modeling

00:47:54.719 --> 00:47:57.239
and machine learning methods are cheaper and more accurate.

00:47:57.239 --> 00:47:59.600
So it's really pretty,

00:47:59.600 --> 00:48:00.919
once you get out of computer vision

00:48:00.919 --> 00:48:02.560
and language translation,

00:48:03.479 --> 00:48:05.919
a lot of this stuff is in the research stage,

00:48:05.919 --> 00:48:07.040
it's in the speculative stage.

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:08.080
And I think there's different approaches

00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:09.520
you could take to that.

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:11.639
Right now, creating an image classifier

00:48:11.639 --> 00:48:14.360
that has a super high accuracy is just completely trivial.

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:16.959
So that field, that frontier is explored

00:48:16.959 --> 00:48:18.520
and understood and applicable.

00:48:19.879 --> 00:48:22.760
But in other cases, the frontier is far away.

00:48:23.639 --> 00:48:25.080
So you could wait and see, wait till,

00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:27.879
okay, I do this type of time series forecasting,

00:48:27.879 --> 00:48:29.719
it's not proven that deep learning helps me,

00:48:29.719 --> 00:48:31.159
I'll just wait and see until it is proven

00:48:31.159 --> 00:48:32.719
and then I'll apply it then.

00:48:32.719 --> 00:48:34.600
Another approach could be to try to see

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:36.520
what contemporary research is doing,

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:38.360
see both formal research

00:48:38.360 --> 00:48:40.639
and what people are publishing on the web,

00:48:40.639 --> 00:48:43.040
and evaluate that and try that with your data

00:48:43.040 --> 00:48:45.600
and your work and see if it improves things.

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:47.679
And yet another approach is to actually try to,

00:48:47.679 --> 00:48:50.280
in your field of endeavor, try to approach the frontier,

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:52.360
try to see if you can find novel applications

00:48:52.719 --> 00:48:54.120
for deep neural nets.

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:57.320
So all of this requires,

00:48:57.320 --> 00:49:00.080
it's great to show examples that do interesting things,

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:02.479
but it does require a lot of work and time

00:49:02.479 --> 00:49:05.520
and patience and iteration to get these models to work well.

00:49:05.520 --> 00:49:08.639
So in practice, there's a huge amount of experimentation

00:49:08.639 --> 00:49:11.719
that's done with model architecture, with hyperparameters.

00:49:11.719 --> 00:49:15.560
And what happens is people gain better intuition

00:49:15.560 --> 00:49:18.040
about what sorts of models and layers

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:20.199
and other things work well

00:49:20.199 --> 00:49:22.760
for the class of data problems that they have.

00:49:23.719 --> 00:49:25.159
So it tends to require a lot of iteration,

00:49:25.159 --> 00:49:27.080
it tends to require a lot of compute power,

00:49:27.080 --> 00:49:29.600
and it sort of tends to require some related tools

00:49:29.600 --> 00:49:31.679
to help you kind of streamline your workflow

00:49:31.679 --> 00:49:33.280
and make the most of the compute power you have.

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:36.320
And that's kind of the next piece that I want to talk about

00:49:36.320 --> 00:49:39.560
is the tools that we've built to help you with the process.

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:42.199
Kind of first and foremost is using GPUs.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:47.479
Some deep learning models work great on CPUs.

00:49:47.520 --> 00:49:51.600
Ones that use convolution or recurrent neural networks

00:49:51.600 --> 00:49:53.239
tend to be very slow on CPUs.

00:49:53.239 --> 00:49:57.360
So if you go to our TensorFlow for R website,

00:49:57.360 --> 00:49:58.320
there's a bunch of resources

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:00.199
about different ways you can use GPUs.

00:50:00.199 --> 00:50:04.439
One is if you have a high-end NVIDIA graphics card,

00:50:04.439 --> 00:50:07.639
you can use a GPU on your local system.

00:50:07.639 --> 00:50:10.840
There's cloud services that let you do batch jobs

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:12.199
that use GPUs.

00:50:12.199 --> 00:50:14.840
You can set up a cloud server with RStudio Server

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:17.760
on Google Compute or Amazon or Azure.

00:50:17.760 --> 00:50:19.199
And there's even ways to actually have

00:50:19.199 --> 00:50:21.800
a virtual cloud Linux desktop that has a GPU.

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:23.639
So all that's covered on our GPU page.

00:50:23.639 --> 00:50:24.879
I won't talk about that further,

00:50:24.879 --> 00:50:27.840
but it's definitely something to look into

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:29.000
if you want to explore.

00:50:30.159 --> 00:50:31.959
We have another package called tfruns,

00:50:31.959 --> 00:50:33.879
stands for TensorFlow runs.

00:50:33.879 --> 00:50:36.760
And the idea here is that because

00:50:36.760 --> 00:50:38.120
a huge amount of experimentation

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:39.520
is required with deep learning models,

00:50:39.520 --> 00:50:42.000
you're going to run a ton of training jobs.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.919
Instead of using the source function to run those jobs,

00:50:44.919 --> 00:50:46.679
you use a function called training run.

00:50:46.679 --> 00:50:48.320
And what training run does is it records

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:49.520
everything about that job.

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:51.320
The source code, the output,

00:50:51.320 --> 00:50:53.159
the performance of the model,

00:50:53.159 --> 00:50:54.879
the hyperparameters you use for the model.

00:50:54.879 --> 00:50:56.959
And then you basically have a data frame

00:50:56.959 --> 00:50:59.439
at the end for all the model runs that you've ever done.

00:50:59.439 --> 00:51:01.199
And then you can compute on that data frame

00:51:01.199 --> 00:51:03.360
to try to understand better what's working well

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:05.080
and not working well.

00:51:05.080 --> 00:51:06.840
It also gives you reports on each runs

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:09.000
that summarize, again, the code, the model,

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.399
the metrics, the performance of the model.

00:51:11.399 --> 00:51:13.959
So every single time you do a training run,

00:51:13.959 --> 00:51:15.800
one of these reports is generated.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:16.879
And then you can compare runs.

00:51:16.879 --> 00:51:19.479
So if you find, okay, I've examined my data frame.

00:51:19.479 --> 00:51:22.760
I found that these are my best two performing models.

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:23.800
What was different about them?

00:51:23.800 --> 00:51:24.719
And you can see in this case,

00:51:24.719 --> 00:51:26.199
it's showing a source code diff saying

00:51:26.199 --> 00:51:27.879
I changed two things in the source code.

00:51:27.879 --> 00:51:30.560
And that accounts for that difference in performance.

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:35.159
And there's another piece called flags,

00:51:35.159 --> 00:51:37.080
which basically says if there's important aspects

00:51:37.080 --> 00:51:40.159
of my model, it's good to externalize those,

00:51:40.159 --> 00:51:41.439
get them out of my source code

00:51:41.439 --> 00:51:43.560
so that I can kind of pass these flags

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:45.360
to my script as a parameter.

00:51:45.360 --> 00:51:48.320
So you can see I'm defining a set of flags here.

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:51.199
And then I'm using the flags when I define a layer.

00:51:51.199 --> 00:51:52.600
And then when I train the model,

00:51:52.600 --> 00:51:54.000
I'm passing one of the flags.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
They're basically kind of command line parameters

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.580
for your script that let you easily vary things.

00:51:59.959 --> 00:52:02.719
And then that in turn enables this construct

00:52:02.719 --> 00:52:04.360
called a tuning run that says,

00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:07.879
okay, I've got two types of dropout.

00:52:07.879 --> 00:52:12.280
In this case, I'm gonna vary dropout from 0.2 to 0.4.

00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:14.360
And I want you to try every combination

00:52:14.360 --> 00:52:17.320
of those two hyperparameters

00:52:17.320 --> 00:52:19.320
and then tell me what the best model is.

00:52:19.320 --> 00:52:21.919
And if the number of combinations gets very, very large,

00:52:21.919 --> 00:52:23.360
you know, into the thousands,

00:52:23.360 --> 00:52:24.879
then you can actually sample from that

00:52:24.879 --> 00:52:29.399
and only run 50 training jobs

00:52:29.399 --> 00:52:30.560
rather than thousands of them

00:52:30.560 --> 00:52:33.080
to try to evaluate what the best model is.

00:52:33.080 --> 00:52:35.139
But these sort of tools end up being critical

00:52:35.139 --> 00:52:37.320
to getting deep learning models that perform well

00:52:37.679 --> 00:52:39.959
because you have to try so many different things.

00:52:41.439 --> 00:52:45.560
The Cloud ML package is our interface to Google Cloud ML.

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:48.280
And Google Cloud ML basically lets you train models,

00:52:48.280 --> 00:52:51.679
sort of, you sort of submit batch jobs to Cloud ML

00:52:51.679 --> 00:52:52.840
and then the model trains.

00:52:52.840 --> 00:52:55.600
And what's really cool about it is that they have GPUs

00:52:55.600 --> 00:52:57.800
and they actually have some really, really fast GPUs

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:02.479
and even machines that have multiple fast GPUs available.

00:53:02.479 --> 00:53:03.959
And they also have a service for doing

00:53:03.959 --> 00:53:06.199
this hyperparameter tuning that I just talked about.

00:53:06.199 --> 00:53:08.439
So the idea is you want to work

00:53:08.439 --> 00:53:09.600
from the comfort of your laptop

00:53:09.600 --> 00:53:11.320
with smaller down-sampled data.

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:13.360
And then when you want to actually do your training,

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:15.060
that's going to take three hours.

00:53:15.060 --> 00:53:17.239
You submit it to Cloud ML and then it takes 20 minutes,

00:53:17.239 --> 00:53:18.939
hopefully, instead of three hours.

00:53:20.080 --> 00:53:21.659
Similar to Training Run,

00:53:21.659 --> 00:53:23.760
there's a function called Cloud ML Train.

00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:25.560
And when you give an R script to Cloud ML Train,

00:53:25.560 --> 00:53:27.159
it'll actually upload the contents

00:53:27.159 --> 00:53:28.679
of the working directory to Cloud ML.

00:53:28.679 --> 00:53:31.600
It'll actually figure out what packages you're using

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:33.360
and make sure those packages are installed

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:35.840
on the Cloud ML server.

00:53:36.479 --> 00:53:37.320
And then when I do this,

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:38.919
I can actually specify the kind of hardware I want to use.

00:53:38.919 --> 00:53:41.959
So in this case, I'm saying use a standard GPU.

00:53:41.959 --> 00:53:45.060
In this case, I'm saying use like super pumped up,

00:53:45.060 --> 00:53:48.219
latest and greatest NVIDIA Tesla GPU.

00:53:49.580 --> 00:53:51.239
And then you kind of similarly,

00:53:51.239 --> 00:53:53.560
once you do a training job, you can collect the results.

00:53:53.560 --> 00:53:54.919
You can get all the files that were generated.

00:53:54.919 --> 00:53:57.040
You can get a report about how it did.

00:53:57.040 --> 00:53:59.560
You can see all your jobs in a data frame.

00:54:00.639 --> 00:54:03.199
And then once, if you're using these flags

00:54:03.199 --> 00:54:04.300
that I talked about,

00:54:04.300 --> 00:54:06.419
you can actually do hyper parameter tuning.

00:54:06.419 --> 00:54:08.340
So in this case, I've defined my flags

00:54:08.340 --> 00:54:11.979
and I've used them in kind of composing my model.

00:54:11.979 --> 00:54:14.939
And I can write a YAML file that I give to Cloud ML

00:54:14.939 --> 00:54:16.699
and I can say, here's the parameters.

00:54:16.699 --> 00:54:18.620
Here's how I want to vary them.

00:54:18.620 --> 00:54:22.540
And here's the metric that I'm trying to optimize for.

00:54:22.540 --> 00:54:24.620
In this case, it's validation accuracy.

00:54:24.620 --> 00:54:26.199
And here's how many trials I want to run.

00:54:26.199 --> 00:54:29.500
So this is a way to search over huge spaces of models.

00:54:29.500 --> 00:54:32.080
And it's all done remotely in the cloud.

00:54:32.239 --> 00:54:34.000
And you're kind of just only charged

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:38.199
for the compute that you use in the execution of those jobs.

00:54:39.280 --> 00:54:42.679
So when the job is done, you get a summary of all the jobs,

00:54:42.679 --> 00:54:47.159
what the flags were, and what the accuracy was.

00:54:47.159 --> 00:54:50.760
And so you can figure out what architecture

00:54:50.760 --> 00:54:53.060
and hyper parameters work best for your model.

00:54:55.840 --> 00:54:56.679
I talked a little bit earlier

00:54:56.679 --> 00:54:59.020
about how TensorFlow models can be deployed

00:54:59.020 --> 00:55:02.000
without an R runtime dependency.

00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:04.179
So the tf.deploy package has tools

00:55:04.179 --> 00:55:05.780
that facilitate doing that.

00:55:05.780 --> 00:55:06.800
I won't get into all the,

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:08.639
there's actually another talk about this

00:55:08.639 --> 00:55:10.879
in the interop session one

00:55:10.879 --> 00:55:12.760
that will go into more detail about this.

00:55:12.760 --> 00:55:15.300
But the idea is you get a model, you export it,

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:17.840
and then you can, for example,

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:21.320
serve that model using a REST HTTP API.

00:55:22.199 --> 00:55:24.040
You can serve it using an open source project

00:55:24.040 --> 00:55:26.580
that Google has called TensorFlow Serving.

00:55:26.580 --> 00:55:29.199
You can serve it from RStudio Connect.

00:55:29.199 --> 00:55:30.800
You can serve it from Cloud ML.

00:55:30.800 --> 00:55:33.179
So these models, the nice thing is these models

00:55:33.179 --> 00:55:35.120
can be served from a whole wide variety

00:55:35.120 --> 00:55:36.040
of different sources.

00:55:36.040 --> 00:55:38.439
And again, there's no R runtime dependency

00:55:38.439 --> 00:55:40.080
for serving the model.

00:55:40.080 --> 00:55:41.500
It's very easy to embed these models

00:55:41.500 --> 00:55:43.040
inside Shiny applications.

00:55:43.040 --> 00:55:45.479
Couple examples of that on the gallery.

00:55:45.479 --> 00:55:47.600
And then what's really cool

00:55:47.600 --> 00:55:49.179
is you can actually deploy these models

00:55:49.179 --> 00:55:50.879
not just to servers,

00:55:50.879 --> 00:55:53.360
but you can deploy them to embedded devices.

00:55:53.360 --> 00:55:55.760
You can deploy them to mobile phones.

00:55:55.760 --> 00:55:57.399
You can actually deploy them into the browser.

00:55:57.399 --> 00:55:59.320
There's a library called Keras.js

00:55:59.320 --> 00:56:00.760
and a library called DeepLearn.js

00:56:01.719 --> 00:56:02.840
that lets you take TensorFlow and Keras models

00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:04.639
and run them directly in JavaScript.

00:56:04.639 --> 00:56:08.959
So this idea that a model is this graph

00:56:08.959 --> 00:56:10.439
that's independent of the programming language

00:56:10.439 --> 00:56:12.719
used to create it is a really, really powerful one,

00:56:12.719 --> 00:56:14.719
and I think, hopefully, one that we can take

00:56:14.719 --> 00:56:16.800
a great advantage of in R.

00:56:16.800 --> 00:56:19.000
Again, there's a talk talking about deployment

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:20.159
in the interop session.

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:25.000
So what are the big, big takeaways

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:28.879
that I hope you internalize a little bit from this talk?

00:56:28.879 --> 00:56:30.719
One is think of TensorFlow

00:56:30.719 --> 00:56:34.560
not just as a library that people use for deep learning.

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:36.959
It is a general-purpose computing library,

00:56:36.959 --> 00:56:38.080
and it has lots to offer us,

00:56:38.080 --> 00:56:39.620
and we should be exploring those things

00:56:39.620 --> 00:56:41.959
like what has been done with the Greta project.

00:56:43.199 --> 00:56:45.040
Deep learning has made a lot of great progress

00:56:45.040 --> 00:56:46.040
in some fields,

00:56:46.040 --> 00:56:48.000
and a lot of people are working hard

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.360
at making progress in other fields,

00:56:50.360 --> 00:56:52.879
and it's likely to increase in importance in those fields.

00:56:52.879 --> 00:56:55.300
It's hard to say exactly how much,

00:56:55.300 --> 00:56:56.659
but I think it's something

00:56:56.659 --> 00:56:57.760
that a lot of people are working on.

00:56:57.760 --> 00:56:59.320
It's gonna be relevant to our work,

00:56:59.320 --> 00:57:01.399
and I think, most importantly,

00:57:01.399 --> 00:57:05.340
the work that we've done for the TensorFlow R interfaces,

00:57:05.340 --> 00:57:07.639
we have a great set of high-level APIs,

00:57:07.639 --> 00:57:10.600
different levels, we have high-level and low-level,

00:57:10.600 --> 00:57:12.820
so doing deep learning in R is now really easy,

00:57:12.820 --> 00:57:14.120
and you have the state-of-the-art tools,

00:57:14.120 --> 00:57:15.199
you have the tools that are used

00:57:15.199 --> 00:57:17.139
by researchers and practitioners,

00:57:18.560 --> 00:57:21.439
the best tools used by researchers and practitioners today,

00:57:21.439 --> 00:57:22.639
and we have low-level interfaces

00:57:22.639 --> 00:57:24.280
for doing more innovative things.

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:29.239
There are a couple more talks in the Interop track at 11.

00:57:29.239 --> 00:57:32.280
There's a talk from Michael Quinn, who's from Google,

00:57:32.280 --> 00:57:34.520
and he's gonna talk about modeling predictions

00:57:34.520 --> 00:57:35.899
on Google Store data,

00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:38.600
using the tools that we talked about today,

00:57:38.600 --> 00:57:41.379
and then we have this deployment talk

00:57:41.379 --> 00:57:42.719
that comes immediately after that,

00:57:42.719 --> 00:57:45.040
so check those out if you're interested.

00:57:45.040 --> 00:57:48.600
There's a website that we have, tensorflow.rstudio.com,

00:57:48.600 --> 00:57:50.379
that really has a lot of the content

00:57:50.379 --> 00:57:53.040
that I covered in this talk, obviously much deeper.

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:55.139
That website covers everything you need to know

00:57:55.139 --> 00:57:57.100
about TensorFlow and R,

00:57:58.080 --> 00:57:59.639
and this is actually really important.

00:57:59.639 --> 00:58:01.000
If you wanna get into this,

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.439
there are two books that I highly recommend that you read.

00:58:03.439 --> 00:58:05.560
They're very different books.

00:58:05.560 --> 00:58:07.639
One is this book, Deep Learning with R,

00:58:07.639 --> 00:58:10.219
that just came out a couple days ago,

00:58:10.219 --> 00:58:11.959
and my name's on the cover,

00:58:11.959 --> 00:58:15.159
but I didn't write any of the prose in the book.

00:58:15.159 --> 00:58:16.879
It's written by Francois,

00:58:16.879 --> 00:58:18.919
who's the gentleman who created Keras,

00:58:18.919 --> 00:58:22.679
and I took his book, his Keras book,

00:58:22.679 --> 00:58:24.399
which covers the Python interface,

00:58:24.399 --> 00:58:26.919
and I worked with him to adapt it to R.

00:58:26.919 --> 00:58:28.840
So this is a book that really covers

00:58:28.840 --> 00:58:31.360
the concepts behind deep learning.

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:33.239
Mostly it's a conceptual book,

00:58:33.239 --> 00:58:35.399
but all of the examples are done in R,

00:58:35.399 --> 00:58:36.879
using the Keras interface.

00:58:37.840 --> 00:58:39.800
There's actually no math in this book at all.

00:58:39.800 --> 00:58:41.879
It's all of the mathematical intuition

00:58:41.879 --> 00:58:44.399
is provided by showing you R code.

00:58:44.399 --> 00:58:45.479
So that's one book.

00:58:45.479 --> 00:58:48.959
Great conceptual introduction, all code, no math.

00:58:48.959 --> 00:58:50.919
The other book is kind of the most important book,

00:58:50.919 --> 00:58:52.879
I think, right now in the field,

00:58:52.879 --> 00:58:54.879
sort of providing the conceptual foundation

00:58:54.879 --> 00:58:55.840
for deep learning.

00:58:55.840 --> 00:58:57.120
This book has no code at all.

00:58:57.120 --> 00:58:57.959
It's all math.

00:58:57.959 --> 00:59:00.959
So depending on how you learn,

00:59:00.959 --> 00:59:02.560
and how you like to approach things,

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:03.639
read one or the other first.

00:59:03.639 --> 00:59:05.320
But these, they're very different books,

00:59:05.320 --> 00:59:07.120
but I think they're both essential.

00:59:08.239 --> 00:59:09.639
So thank you very much.

00:59:09.639 --> 00:59:13.120
These slides are available at the URL displayed here.

00:59:13.120 --> 00:59:14.739
And the other thing I would urge you to do

00:59:14.739 --> 00:59:16.360
is if you're interested in this stuff,

00:59:16.360 --> 00:59:18.139
on our TensorFlow for R blog,

00:59:18.139 --> 00:59:22.300
we're posting new examples and case studies all the time.

00:59:22.300 --> 00:59:23.959
So if you wanna kind of keep up with

00:59:23.959 --> 00:59:24.800
the work that we're doing,

00:59:24.800 --> 00:59:25.679
and other people are doing,

00:59:25.679 --> 00:59:28.020
subscribing to that blog is a great way to do that.

00:59:28.020 --> 00:59:29.179
So thanks very much,

00:59:29.179 --> 00:59:31.419
and I'd love to hear what questions people have.

00:59:31.979 --> 00:59:32.820
Thank you.

00:59:36.439 --> 00:59:37.260
Thank you.

